While the beliefthat man possesses the characteristics of the lower animals is very ancient, the form of the myth which Horace gives here is not found in any ear- lier author.—principi: principal, primordial; ‘primitive clay)— coactus: for all the elements had been exhausted in making the other animals; therefore Prome- theus was obliged to take a por- tion from each creature (undique) for man.
